ðŸ†š Low-Fidelity vs. High-Fidelity Wireframes
Understanding the difference between low- and high-fidelity wireframes helps teams choose the right tool for the right phase in the design process.

ðŸ”¹ Low-Fidelity Wireframes
Basic, hand-drawn or sketched.

Focus on structure and layout, not detail.

No color, images, or branding.

Often done on paper or whiteboards or with simple tools like Balsamiq.

ðŸ•’ Used When:

Early brainstorming or ideation stage.

Exploring multiple layout options quickly.

Sharing initial ideas with stakeholders.

ðŸ“Œ Example: A black-and-white sketch showing placement of a nav bar, hero section, and CTA button.

ðŸ”¸ High-Fidelity Wireframes
Detailed and close to the final design.

Include fonts, spacing, icons, and placeholder content.

Sometimes interactive (clickable).

Built using tools like Figma, Adobe XD, or Sketch.

ðŸ•’ Used When:

Later stages of design.

Preparing for usability testing.

Handing off to developers.

ðŸ“Œ Example: A realistic screen mockup with labeled input fields, navigation, and hover states.
